Description: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a concave surface with wood impression, probably from a bolt. In the break the impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.2cm. The upper side is flat with the lateral sides bending downwards sharply and showing finger imprints. The middle part of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Recognisable is a cartouche in the centre with (Mn-kheper-R')|. At the right and left of it each another element encircled in an oval surrounding that does not seem to be a cartouche, maybe spirals? Underneath all this three elements a horizontal line and underneath that a winged scarab.
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
